{"id":"nucl-th/9312001","submitter":"Ruprecht Machleidt","authors":"G. E. Brown and R. Machleidt","title":"Comment on \"Phase-Shift Analysis of NN Scattering Below 160 Mev:\n  Indication of a Strong Tensor Force\"","comments":"12 pages LaTeX and 2 figures (available upon request), UI-NTH-9312","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"nucl-th","license":null,"abstract":"  In his recent publication of a NN phase shift analysis below 160 MeV, Henneck\nreports relatively large values for the mixing parameter $\\epsilon_1$. Based on\nthese results, Henneck suggests that the strength of the $\\rho$-meson tensor\ncoupling to the nucleon may be weaker than used in present day NN interactions,\nlike the Paris or Bonn potentials. We point out that at low energies ( < 100\nMeV ) there is very little sensitivity to the strength of the $\\rho$ coupling,\ndue to the compensating effect of the second order tensor term. In order to\nestablish sensitivity, one has to go to energies > 200 MeV, where the second\norder contribution has gone out. As it happens, the $\\epsilon_1$ mixing\nparameter is well determined in the region of energies 200--300 MeV, and there\nis agreement with the predictions by the Paris and Bonn potentials; whereas the\nweak-$\\rho$ model is about 50\\% above the data. This and additional\nconsiderations in triplet $P$-waves re-confirm that NN scattering requires the\nstrong $\\rho$, consistent with the $\\pi\\pi-N\\bar{N}$ partial-wave analysis by\nH\\\"ohler and Pietarinen.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 1 Dec 1993 17:52:30 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-09-25"}
